### removeDependencesFromMultipleStores() {#a0600a51b42956b4e041baa101a3c047a}

<MemberDefinition
  prototype={<>void anonymous&#95;namespace&#123;LoopLoadElimination.cpp&#125;::LoadEliminationForLoop::removeDependencesFromMultipleStores (std::forward&#95;list&lt; <a href="/docs/api/structs/anonymous-namespace-looploadelimination-cpp-/storetoloadforwardingcandidate">StoreToLoadForwardingCandidate</a> &gt; &amp; Candidates)</>}
  labels = {["inline"]}>
If a load has multiple candidates associated (i.e.

different stores), it means that it could be forwarding from multiple stores depending on control flow. Remove these candidates.

Here, we rely on LAA to include the relevant loop-independent dependences. LAA is known to omit these in the very simple case when the read and the write within an alias set always takes place using the <em>same</em> pointer.

However, we know that this is not the case here, i.e. we can rely on LAA to provide us with loop-independent dependences for the cases we&#39;re interested. Consider the case for example where a loop-independent dependece S1-&gt;S2 invalidates the forwarding S3-&gt;S2. 

<CodeBlock>
    A&#91;i&#93;   = ...   (S1)
    ...    = A&#91;i&#93;  (S2)
    A&#91;i+1&#93; = ...   (S3)
</CodeBlock>

LAA will perform dependence analysis here because there are two <em>different</em> pointers involved in the same alias set (&amp;A&#91;i&#93; and &amp;A&#91;i+1&#93;).

Definition at line <a href="/docs/api/files/lib/lib/transforms/lib/transforms/scalar/looploadelimination-cpp/#l00266">266</a> of file <a href="/docs/api/files/lib/lib/transforms/lib/transforms/scalar/looploadelimination-cpp">LoopLoadElimination.cpp</a>.
</MemberDefinition>
